    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/05-posttraining-alignment/01-sft-instruction-tuning.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Response-only loss masking: the transformer sees one flat sequence, but gradients flow only from the assistant-response tokens, so SFT rewards reply quality rather than re-predicting the instruction.; The superficial alignment hypothesis (LIMA): knowledge already lives in the pretraining weights; SFT only teaches the model to access and present it in the right format, so a small curated dataset beats a large noisy one.; SFT is Stage 1 of a three-stage recipe (SFT -> Reward Modeling -> RL alignment), and it gives RL a strong behavioral prior to start from.; Catastrophic forgetting: fine-tuning moves the weights out of the broad pretraining optimum toward a narrow SFT optimum; a large LR / many epochs overshoots and erases general skills, while small LR, short training, replay, and LoRA keep the model near the shared basin.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  sft-memory-budget-full-vs-qlora, refusal-calibration-contrast-set\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
